passages.text: 2Q Beat w/ 2H Upside Divers In Place; Mgmt Takes & Model Implications

FIVE reported 2Q adj. EPS of \(\) 0.81\((\geq\) Street\) \ \(0.61\) and vs. mgmt's \(\) 0.50-\ \(0.62\) guide) comprised of same- store- sales \(+12.4\%\) (above mgmt's \(+7 - 9\%\) guidance/ Street \(+8.9\%\) ), \(+69\) bps of gross margin expansion (vs. Street 12bps contraction) and 22bps of SG&A leverage (vs. Street 16bps deleverage), equating to \(+91\) bps of adj. EBIT margin expansion y/y to \(5.4\%\) (vs. Street \(4.2\%\) ).

Digging deeper on the topline - management clarified that May/June price adjustments translated to better- than- anticipated unit elasticity (recall, a key incremental point from our fieldwork highlighted in our 7/21 Preview). Importantly, management noted that better unit elasticity trends have continued into August/3QTD (exceeding mgmt's initial 1:1 elasticity assumption), with our model holding the July +MSD/HSD \(\% 2\) - yr stack into August w/ mgmt. citing "overall, we feel really good about where the business is and feel that the guide is appropriate." On upside opportunity - holding 2Q's \(+6.7\%\) 2- year stack through 2H translates to \(+7.6\%\) same- store- sales in FY25 ( \(>mgmt's + 5 - 7\%\) guide) with pricing flow- through (3 months of 3Q vs. 1 month in 2Q) representing "stack- breaking" incremental upside noting that 4Q's low- single- digit same- store- sales guide stands unchanged relative to March 19th (= beat/raise 2H setup).

Looking ahead, management raised the FY25 adj. EPS guidance to \(\) 4.76\(to\) \ \(5.16\) (vs. \(\) 4.25-\ \(4.72 prior / and\) \ \(5\%\) above Street \(\) 4.71\(based on sales of\) \ \(4.44 - 4.52B\) ( \(>\) 4.33- 4.42B prior), which reflects same- store- sales \(+5 - 7\%\) (above \(+3 - 5\%\) prior / Street \(+5.0\%\) ) and 150 new store openings (= prior guidance). On the bottom- line, mgmt raised the operating margin guide to contract - 130bps to \(- 7.9\%\) at the midpoint (vs. \(7.3\%\) prior and above Street \(7.5\%\) ) with (i) gross margin contraction equating to \(\sim 60\) bps by our math primarily reflecting costs from absorbing tariffs net of management's mitigation strategies (= 130bps pressure on the full year) partially offset by fixed cost leverage, and (ii) SG&A deleverage equating to \(\sim 60\) bps deleverage on our math reflecting higher incentive compensation partially offset by fixed cost leverage.

On tariffs = management lowered the 3Q tariff impact (net of mitigation) to - 160bps (vs. - 220bps prior) driven by (i) better than plan unit elasticity from price increases, (ii) sales mix benefit, and (iii) changes in cost mitigation strategies. On 4Q, management clarified the initial - 225bps tariff assumption remains unchanged (and - 60bps lower than 3Q) due to lower sales anticipated in 4Q vs. 3Q with aforementioned 4Q top- line conservatism pointing to 10bps of incremental margin flow- through per comp point (= 30- 45bps incremental upside opportunity).

Near- term, management guided 3Q adj. EPS to \(\) 0.12-\ \(0.24\) ( \(>\) Street \(\) 0.01) based on same- store- sales \(+5 - 7\%\) (above Street \(+2.0\%\) ), \(\sim 100\) bps of gross margin pressure y/y (with fixed cost leverage partially offsetting a - 160bps tariff headwind

We rate FIVE Neutral. FIVE faces 2025 margin headwinds to constrain the flow through (labor investment and exec compensation) as it works through initiatives to right the business (pricing, product, etc.), but we see potential operational P/L inflection across (i) same- store sales (notably 1H25 with 2H merchandising opportunity), unit growth (potential FY26 acceleration), and gross margin (2Q25 pricing / 2H25 shrink upside not in our model).
Our Dec '26 price target of \(\) 154\(is unchanged & based on - 27x our FY27E EPS of\) \ \(5.67\) ( \(=\) FIVE's trailing 5- yr multiple).

vs. Street 30.7%) and SG&A deleverage of \(\sim 100\) bps (primarily driven by \(\sim 70\) bps of incentive compensation headwinds), equating to operating margin contraction of \(\sim 230\) bps to \(1.0\%\) at the midpoint ( \(>\) Street \(- 0.4\%\) ).

- & 4Q's Low-Single Implied Guide Unchanged Relative to March. Looking ahead to 4Q, mgmt cited its FY25 guidance points to 4Q SSS implied +LSD% (=450bps below 3Q guidance at the midpoint). Specifically, mgmt remains focused on the core customer (= pre-teen & teen) by (i) returning to extreme values with wow appeal via reduction in SKU's (w/mgmt citing oppty to reduce well over 20%) and number of price points, (ii) getting back to trend-right product, and (iii) executing to a more consistent, fun and enjoyable in-store experience.

( \(= 130\) bps pressure on the full year) partially offset by fixed cost leverage and improved inventory positions by our math, and (ii) SG&A deleverage equating to \(\sim 60\) bps deleverage on our math from higher incentive compensation partially offset by fixed cost leverage. Looking ahead to 4Q25, management anticipates operating margin contraction of \(\sim 320\) bps in 4Q to \(\sim 15.0\%\) (vs. Street \(15.3\%\) ) with \(\sim 70\%\) of the pressure tied to GPM ( \(\sim 38.3\%\) GPM \(=\) Street) and \(30\%\) from SG&A \(= 23.2\%\) SG&A rate \(>\) Street \(23.0\%\)

Model Implications: We model FY25 EPS of \(\) 4.97\(vs. Street\) \ \(4.71\) ) and FY26 EPS of \(\) 5.15\(vs. Street\) \ \(5.24\) ). Remain Neutral with \(\) 154\(Dec'26 price target unchanged based on \~27x our FY27E EPS of\) \ \(5.66\) ( \(=\) FIVE's trailing 5-year multiple), with aforementioned 4Q25 upside opportunity and subsequent fixed cost and tariff flowthrough, we see FY27 EPS power of \~\) 6.30\(vs. Street\) \ \(5.92\) ) pointing to \(\) 170\(equity value.

- Boss'2Q P/L Review: FIVE reported 2Q same-store-sales of \(+12.4\%\) (above mgmt's \(+7\) to \(+9\%\) comp guidance) comprised of a (i) transactions growth of \(+8.7\%\) y/y (vs. \(+6.2\%\) in 1Q) representing the second consecutive quarter of positive transaction, and (ii) \(+3.4\%\) growth in average ticket (vs. 1Q \(+0.9\%\) ). On margins, 2Q GPM expanded \(+69\) bps y/y (above mgmt's initial "slight pressure" guidance) to \(33.4\%\) due to fixed cost leverage on the \(+12.4\%\) comp, partially offset by the net impact of tariffs. On expenses, 2Q adj. SG&A \(\) 5\(grew \(+22.7\%\) y/y and leveraged 22bps y/y to \(28.1\%\) driven by fixed cost leverage on the \(+12.4\%\) comp, partially offset by higher incentive compensation, equating to a \(5.4\%\) adj. EBIT margin (above mgmt's initial \(3.9\%\) guide at the midpoint).

- Balance Sheet Snapshot: FIVE ended 2Q with \(\) 670\(M of cash and short-term investments against no outstanding debt. Inventories ended 2Q Flat y/y (vs 1Q \(+11\%\) ) with average store inventories up \(+12\%\) y/y - translating to a -1,240bps inventory-to-sales spread on average inventory per store and same-store-sales (w/ comps \(+12.4\%\) ). FIVE opened 32 new stores, ending the quarter with 1,858 stores (+11.5% y/y). Looking forward, mgmt expects to complete 150 new store openings.
